{"key":"post-9560801","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9560801</id>\n<content>I think you'll find that alternating layers will work better than a thorough mixing.&amp;nbsp; Be sure to have a top layer of straight manure with no grains showing on the surface.&amp;nbsp; The reason is that when you layer the spawn, it seems to knit back together faster than with individual kernels infiltrating the manure.&amp;nbsp; However you mix the spawn and bulk substrate, leave a layer of bulk on top as said.&amp;nbsp; When grains are left exposed on top, contamination sets in much easier.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9560811</next>\n<prev>9560765</prev>\n<first>9560723</first>\n<last>9563313</last>\n<when>1231303615</when>\n<utime>01/07/09 06:46 AM</utime>\n</post>"}